==English==
{{wikipedia|dab=disdain}}

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|desdeignier|lang=fro}} (modern French {{term|dédaigner|lang=fr}}).

===Pronunciation===
* {{enPR|dĭs-dān'}}, {{IPA|/dɪsˈdeɪn/}}, {{X-SAMPA|/dIs"deIn/}}
* {{rhymes|eɪn}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|-}}

# {{uncountable}} A [[feeling]] of [[contempt]] or [[scorn]].
#: ''The cat viewed the cheap supermarket catfood with '''disdain''' and stalked away.''
#* Shakespeare
#*: '''Disdain''' and scorn ride sparkling in her eyes.
# {{obsolete}} That which is worthy to be disdained or regarded with contempt and aversion.
#* Spenser
#*: Most loathsome, filthy, foul, and full of vile '''disdain'''.
# {{obsolete}} The state of being despised; shame.
#: {{rfquotek|Shakespeare}}

